Introduction¶

In this project we aim to forecast energy usage using time-series data.

Results¶

Our final model successfully predicted energy usage based on extrapolated features from the dataset. We enhanced the dataset by adding several time-related columns to help the model identify trends in usage during specific periods. These new columns included the hour, day of the week, quarter, month, year, and day of the year. Among these, the model identified the hour as the most important feature for predicting energy consumption.

While our predicted vs. actual fitting shows that the model performs well for mid-range values, it struggles with extremes, which suggests room for improvement. To address this, future iterations could incorporate weather data to potentially enhance the model's performance.

In [107]:
def create_features(df):
    df = df.copy()
    df['hour']  = df.index.hour
    df['dayofweek']  = df.index.day_of_week
    df['quarter'] = df.index.quarter 
    df['month'] = df.index.month
    df['year'] = df.index.year
    df['dayofyear'] = df.index.day_of_year
    return df
In [108]:
df = create_features(df)

Create our Model¶

In [111]:
train = create_features(train)
test = create_features(test)
In [118]:
features = ['hour', 'dayofweek', 'quarter', 'month', 'year', 'dayofyear']
target = 'PJME_MW'
In [119]:
x_train = train[features]
y_train = train[target]

x_test = test[features]
y_test = test[target]
In [122]:
reg = xgb.XGBRegressor(n_estimators = 1000, early_stopping_rounds = 50, learning_rate = 0.01)
reg.fit(x_train, y_train, eval_set = [(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test)],
        verbose = 100)
